[[File:Bo Bo Gyi, Botahtaung Pagoda, Yangon.jpg|thumb|[[Botahtaung Pagoda]]'s Rohani Bo Bo Gyi shrine and image.]]
'''Bo Bo Gyi''' ({{lang-my|ဘိုးဘိုးကြီး}}, {{IPA-my|bó bó dʑí|pron}}; lit. "great grandfather") traditionally refers to the name of a guardian spirit (called [[nat (spirit)|nat]]) unique to each [[Burmese Buddhism|Burmese Buddhist]] temple or pagoda. Bo Bo Gyi is typically depicted as a nearly life-sized elderly man, dressed in a curved cap and sometimes carrying a cane, to signify old age.<ref name="sad">{{cite book |title=Burma at the turn of the twenty-first century |last=Sadan |first=Mandy |editor=Monique Skidmore |year=2005 |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |location=Hawaii |isbn=978-0-8248-2897-4 |pages=90–111}}</ref> Offerings of scarves and [[longyi|paso]] are common by worshipers.<ref name="sad"/> There are many Bo Bo Gyi shrines throughout the country, and some are more widely respected than others. The Shwenyaungbin (Golden Banyan Tree) Bo Bo Gyi shrine between [[Yangon]] and [[Bago, Burma|Bago]] is often visited by new car owners hoping have their cars blessed by the Bo Bo Gyi spirit at that site.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB121432598657200325|title=Myanmar's Belief in the Dead|date=29 June 2008 | work=The Wall Street Journal}}{{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Myanmar (Burma) |last=Verlag |first=Nelles |year=1998 |publisher=Hunter Publishing |isbn=978-3-88618-415-6 |pages=100}}</ref>
